WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:25.000
Contest, RStudio, Shiny Contest, Making the Shiny Contest, RStudio, Shiny Contest, Making

00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:26.000
the Video

00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:31.160
the Video.

00:00:31.160 --> 00:00:33.619
I want to start by the inspiration behind it first.

00:00:33.619 --> 00:00:36.599
And the inspiration actually was the bookdown contest.

00:00:36.599 --> 00:00:39.880
And this is one thing I want to read off of the slides because I really like UA's words

00:00:39.880 --> 00:00:40.880
here.

00:00:40.880 --> 00:00:44.939
He said, with this contest I want to encourage bookdown users to share your authoring experience

00:00:44.939 --> 00:00:48.680
and the extensions you have developed to make it even easier for other users to write their

00:00:48.680 --> 00:00:51.720
own books, reports and dissertations, etc.

00:00:51.720 --> 00:00:55.279
This was basically the inspiration behind the Shiny Contest as well.

00:00:55.279 --> 00:01:01.480
We really love seeing the apps you all develop and the dashboards and the interactive documents.

00:01:01.480 --> 00:01:06.440
And when you openly share your code and your process with others, it actually is incredibly

00:01:06.440 --> 00:01:09.000
beneficial for the community.

00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:15.320
And we also realized that the user showcase that we had since Shiny Package has been around,

00:01:15.320 --> 00:01:19.919
that featured really fantastic apps actually didn't have links to the code for all of those

00:01:19.919 --> 00:01:25.279
apps and it would be kind of difficult to go back and try to get all of that, especially

00:01:25.279 --> 00:01:27.360
because some of the code gets out of date.

00:01:27.360 --> 00:01:30.239
So we've been thinking about a way to refresh that.

00:01:30.239 --> 00:01:34.800
And we thought, hey, maybe we can make it into a fun game.

00:01:34.800 --> 00:01:35.800
So we did.

00:01:35.800 --> 00:01:37.900
And, my God, it must have been a fun game.

00:01:37.900 --> 00:01:44.040
So we started January 7th and gave a two-month deadline.

00:01:44.040 --> 00:01:45.959
And I was thinking, okay, this is not going to be so bad.

00:01:45.959 --> 00:01:48.199
I can work on other stuff for a while.

00:01:48.199 --> 00:01:50.599
And then you can see that last bit.

00:01:50.599 --> 00:01:52.680
People wait for the last minute, I suppose.

00:01:52.680 --> 00:01:56.720
So we had 136 submissions, which was very, very cool.

00:01:56.720 --> 00:02:02.440
So what I kind of want to talk about first of all is I'm going to show you some amazing

00:02:02.440 --> 00:02:03.440
Shiny apps today.

00:02:03.440 --> 00:02:07.599
And I feel like I've really kind of scored a good talk, because I can show really amazing

00:02:07.599 --> 00:02:11.559
stuff, but I'm not the one who made them.

00:02:11.559 --> 00:02:16.360
But at the same time, I want to also show you what it takes to enter the contest, because

00:02:16.360 --> 00:02:17.360
it's really not much.

00:02:17.520 --> 00:02:19.279
This is all we required.

00:02:19.279 --> 00:02:20.320
Your code.

00:02:20.320 --> 00:02:24.679
Many people use a GitHub repository, though that was not necessarily a requirement.

00:02:24.679 --> 00:02:28.800
We asked that you use an RStudio Cloud project to host your app in.

00:02:28.800 --> 00:02:32.919
There were some cases where that wasn't the case, and we still accepted that.

00:02:32.919 --> 00:02:35.759
I'll mention one important thing in case people are thinking.

00:02:35.759 --> 00:02:39.679
So if you have an app that requires an API key, obviously you're not necessarily going

00:02:39.679 --> 00:02:41.080
to want to share that.

00:02:41.080 --> 00:02:42.440
And we completely understand that.

00:02:42.440 --> 00:02:48.039
So we kind of hope that you will discuss why certain things may or may not be fully

00:02:48.039 --> 00:02:51.960
reproducible by somebody else, but we ask that you kind of provide some description

00:02:51.960 --> 00:02:53.839
as to how I could reproduce it.

00:02:53.839 --> 00:02:56.880
But the idea is that every app is hosted.

00:02:56.880 --> 00:03:00.800
We have the code, and we have it in an RStudio Cloud project, and we also want to link to

00:03:00.800 --> 00:03:01.800
your deployed app.

00:03:01.800 --> 00:03:05.240
And you can simply use Shiny apps.io, or if you have another Shiny server you want to

00:03:05.240 --> 00:03:07.580
deploy on, that's fine as well.

00:03:07.580 --> 00:03:10.119
This is all the requirements that it is.

00:03:10.119 --> 00:03:13.119
And many people added these.

00:03:13.119 --> 00:03:16.399
That was really, really nice to have a brief summary.

00:03:16.399 --> 00:03:19.679
Some of the highlights, because there's a lot in some of these apps, and they may not

00:03:19.679 --> 00:03:24.080
be kind of very clear to the eye right at the beginning, and at least a screenshot so

00:03:24.080 --> 00:03:27.699
we can kind of see what it's going to look like.

00:03:27.699 --> 00:03:32.119
And so this was one of the posts from RStudio community where the submissions are made.

00:03:32.119 --> 00:03:37.119
You can see, I mean, the app is fantastic, but to the entry to the contest, there isn't

00:03:37.119 --> 00:03:38.240
a whole lot going on.

00:03:38.360 --> 00:03:40.279
This was actually one of our runner-ups.

00:03:40.279 --> 00:03:47.320
It was basically, how many of you have heard of Tidy Tuesday?

00:03:47.320 --> 00:03:55.440
People have been kind of submitting their Tidy Tuesday plots on Twitter, so this basically

00:03:55.440 --> 00:03:56.440
pulls from that.

00:03:56.440 --> 00:03:58.119
It's a really cool app.

00:03:58.119 --> 00:04:01.679
And what we said was that we're going to be judging the apps based on their technical

00:04:01.679 --> 00:04:04.160
merit and or their artistic achievement.

00:04:04.160 --> 00:04:07.479
So what does the UI look like?

00:04:07.479 --> 00:04:11.759
And we're going to keep in mind that some apps may score really highly on both of these,

00:04:11.759 --> 00:04:16.440
but some might score higher on one aspect and not the other.

00:04:16.440 --> 00:04:20.980
And we also said that we would be considering feedback and reaction on RStudio community.

00:04:20.980 --> 00:04:25.559
So each submission actually ends up being a post on RStudio community, and we hope that

00:04:25.559 --> 00:04:28.679
people actually like the apps and actually comment.

00:04:28.679 --> 00:04:34.040
I know that some of the apps who were earlier submitted got some feedback, and the participants

00:04:34.040 --> 00:04:39.119
actually got a chance to update them, which was really fantastic.

00:04:39.119 --> 00:04:40.119
What we did.

00:04:40.119 --> 00:04:42.640
That's what we said we were going to do.

00:04:42.640 --> 00:04:47.920
So I actually started by getting the data out of RStudio community and calculated percentiles

00:04:47.920 --> 00:04:54.720
of likes just to see if binning these into categories in terms of being able to maybe

00:04:54.720 --> 00:04:58.720
consider the number of likes would be a good criteria or not.

00:04:58.720 --> 00:05:05.000
And ultimately, even though I did that calculation, that didn't factor a whole lot into it, because

00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:10.519
there was the aspect that if you submit earlier, obviously there's more time for you to get

00:05:10.519 --> 00:05:11.959
more likes.

00:05:11.959 --> 00:05:15.440
That doesn't seem entirely fair if we said that you can submit any time during that time

00:05:15.440 --> 00:05:18.119
frame, but that was useful for us to find out.

00:05:18.119 --> 00:05:22.959
And then what I did is I took a random sample of 15 of these apps, so it wasn't the earlier

00:05:22.959 --> 00:05:28.320
or the later ones, but a truly random sample, and literally went through it all.

00:05:28.320 --> 00:05:29.320
What does the UI look like?

00:05:29.320 --> 00:05:31.040
What does the code look like?

00:05:31.040 --> 00:05:32.320
What was the ambition?

00:05:32.320 --> 00:05:35.279
Did they actually fulfill that?

00:05:35.279 --> 00:05:37.480
And used that to develop a rubric for it.

00:05:37.480 --> 00:05:39.880
So this is what the rubric looked like.

00:05:39.880 --> 00:05:41.880
Five points for technical merit.

00:05:41.880 --> 00:05:44.100
Five points for artistic achievement.

00:05:44.100 --> 00:05:48.920
We also looked at the narrative on the post on RStudio community about how well you described

00:05:48.920 --> 00:05:50.480
what you were trying to do.

00:05:50.480 --> 00:05:56.920
And then those binned categories for feedback.

00:05:56.920 --> 00:05:58.799
And then we had to narrow things down.

00:05:58.799 --> 00:06:05.079
So the first pass is I literally clicked through all of the 136 deployed apps to categorize

00:06:05.079 --> 00:06:08.760
them into either we should consider these further or not.

00:06:08.760 --> 00:06:15.359
And then all of those that were categorized as yes, we should consider these further got

00:06:15.359 --> 00:06:18.720
scored on the rubric that I shared with you.

00:06:18.720 --> 00:06:23.399
And then for any app that was on top 30, I actually went through and tried to reproduce

00:06:23.399 --> 00:06:24.399
them.

00:06:24.399 --> 00:06:28.480
So I went to RStudio Cloud and see if I can actually reproduce it.

00:06:28.480 --> 00:06:32.359
If there wasn't a good reason described for why that couldn't be done, as I mentioned

00:06:32.359 --> 00:06:38.119
something like an API key, then I skipped that one and added another one and narrowed

00:06:38.119 --> 00:06:42.440
things down to about 15 apps, at which point I pinged Joe and I was like, all right, I'm

00:06:42.440 --> 00:06:46.040
going to need one other person to actually go through these.

00:06:46.040 --> 00:06:49.519
So he helped out and we basically picked the winner.

00:06:49.519 --> 00:06:51.519
So it was a process.

00:06:51.519 --> 00:06:55.880
But I think we learned a lot about how we can evaluate these things.

00:06:55.880 --> 00:07:00.000
So I think the mechanism is going to be a little smoother next time.

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:02.440
So let's take a look at what the winners are.

00:07:02.440 --> 00:07:07.640
So the first one is the most technically impressive award, the IC app.

00:07:07.640 --> 00:07:11.040
The IC stands for Interactive Summarized Experiment Explorer.

00:07:11.040 --> 00:07:15.799
So that's by Kevin Ure, Charlotte Sonnison, Federica Marini, and Aaron Lund.

00:07:15.799 --> 00:07:21.320
And the app is incredibly impressive internally.

00:07:22.119 --> 00:07:26.279
So it is designed for interactive exploration of high throughput biological data sets.

00:07:26.279 --> 00:07:29.760
And what it is, is these panels that you're seeing in this screenshot, and I could only

00:07:29.760 --> 00:07:35.720
get so many of them, there are actually six of those, they're really nicely linked together.

00:07:35.720 --> 00:07:39.679
So as you're playing with one and doing some selection on one panel, you can see it reflected

00:07:39.679 --> 00:07:41.119
in the other ones.

00:07:41.119 --> 00:07:45.559
And I think this last bit is going to be relevant to a later on talk that's coming up here.

00:07:45.559 --> 00:07:47.880
You can actually generate a reproducible R script.

00:07:47.880 --> 00:07:52.399
So the idea here is that maybe somebody who is not an R programmer is doing a little bit

00:07:52.399 --> 00:07:58.399
of the analysis interactively, but then they're able to reproduce, they're able to get a reproducible

00:07:58.399 --> 00:08:00.559
R script of the results that they achieved.

00:08:00.559 --> 00:08:07.320
And this predates Shinymeta, so that's incredibly, I think, impressive.

00:08:07.320 --> 00:08:11.000
The next one is just beautiful.

00:08:11.000 --> 00:08:14.239
It was the best design award, 69 Love Songs.

00:08:14.239 --> 00:08:18.839
So that is a, the album is called 69 Love Songs.

00:08:18.839 --> 00:08:19.839
This is by David Smalley.

00:08:19.839 --> 00:08:24.440
He actually has a wonderful blog post explaining what it looks like.

00:08:24.440 --> 00:08:31.000
So there is a lot of technical things going on there that are great, but most importantly,

00:08:31.000 --> 00:08:32.640
it had an incredible visual appeal.

00:08:32.640 --> 00:08:38.080
The colors actually match the album colors, the font matches the font used on the album.

00:08:38.080 --> 00:08:41.599
So a lot of attention to detail happening here.

00:08:41.599 --> 00:08:46.200
And in terms of the analysis, there's web scraping to get the lyrics to begin with,

00:08:46.200 --> 00:08:48.520
and then some text analysis methods.

00:08:48.520 --> 00:08:53.559
And in each one of these tabs, there are different ways of visualizing the text data using a

00:08:53.559 --> 00:08:59.159
variety of different text analysis packages, some of which I actually wasn't really familiar

00:08:59.159 --> 00:09:02.520
with prior to playing around with it.

00:09:02.520 --> 00:09:05.140
And really, really thoughtful storytelling.

00:09:05.140 --> 00:09:11.340
So even if you're not a fan of the Magnetic Fields album, you actually can find something

00:09:11.340 --> 00:09:13.820
to enjoy, I think, in this app.

00:09:13.820 --> 00:09:14.820
And the code is available.

00:09:14.820 --> 00:09:20.419
So if there's an album that you do like, you might want to try to see if it actually will

00:09:20.419 --> 00:09:22.179
carry over.

00:09:22.179 --> 00:09:24.820
The next one is the most fun one.

00:09:24.820 --> 00:09:29.099
I think what happens during the breaks at this conference is a testament to how much

00:09:29.099 --> 00:09:31.500
we love our hexes.

00:09:31.500 --> 00:09:34.739
And this is a hex memory game, basically.

00:09:34.739 --> 00:09:36.659
It is a lot of fun to play.

00:09:36.659 --> 00:09:38.500
It's by Victor Perrier.

00:09:39.140 --> 00:09:43.500
It's not the first game that I've seen on Shiny, but it is incredibly impressive and

00:09:43.500 --> 00:09:45.659
works really, really well.

00:09:45.659 --> 00:09:51.460
And if you actually start looking through the code, even though it is complex, it's

00:09:51.460 --> 00:09:53.020
written so nicely.

00:09:53.020 --> 00:09:58.700
It's very possible to follow along, even if you might be newer to Shiny.

00:09:58.700 --> 00:10:06.619
And so I thought that really kind of earned it the spot on one of the winning apps.

00:10:06.619 --> 00:10:10.900
The last one is so cute.

00:10:10.900 --> 00:10:14.979
And if you have a pet, this is just going to make you feel bad.

00:10:14.979 --> 00:10:15.979
I can just tell you that.

00:10:15.979 --> 00:10:20.539
So if you take your pet to the vet and then you stash away the papers they give you for

00:10:20.539 --> 00:10:24.539
medical records in a folder, thinking if you have an emergency, you're going to be able

00:10:24.539 --> 00:10:26.619
to find it out, forget about it.

00:10:26.619 --> 00:10:28.260
You're not a good enough pet owner.

00:10:28.260 --> 00:10:30.979
I have four cats, so I know how I felt.

00:10:30.979 --> 00:10:33.580
So this is basically an app by Jen Allen.

00:10:33.580 --> 00:10:35.099
It's a dashboard.

00:10:35.619 --> 00:10:37.739
You can see all these tabs.

00:10:37.739 --> 00:10:40.539
And the dogs are called Layla and Lloyd.

00:10:40.539 --> 00:10:44.179
And apparently one of the dogs actually had some medical issues, so there was a lot of

00:10:44.179 --> 00:10:46.940
vet visits that were happening.

00:10:46.940 --> 00:10:52.159
Technically speaking, that timeline visualization that you're seeing is really, really effective

00:10:52.159 --> 00:10:57.020
in terms of figuring out which medication the dogs were taking during which time.

00:10:57.020 --> 00:10:59.380
And also, you can use drill down.

00:10:59.380 --> 00:11:06.940
So click on these bars, drill down, and actually get to a PDF of the certificate, so either

00:11:06.940 --> 00:11:10.659
a record, the medical record, or a vaccination certificate.

00:11:10.659 --> 00:11:16.539
Just an incredible use of the database she was using on the back end and actually an

00:11:16.539 --> 00:11:18.739
ability to interact with that.

00:11:18.739 --> 00:11:21.900
And very cute dogs, so that obviously helps.

00:11:21.900 --> 00:11:22.900
So what did we learn?

00:11:22.900 --> 00:11:27.299
And one of the things we did say initially was that we were going to do awards as in

00:11:27.299 --> 00:11:32.260
an open category and a novice category in order to make sure that people who might be

00:11:32.260 --> 00:11:37.260
just starting off with Shiny also feel like they can be a part of this.

00:11:37.260 --> 00:11:40.460
But I'd say I'd made a mistake that I didn't actually record that information.

00:11:40.460 --> 00:11:45.700
And it's really difficult to look at an app and kind of assign someone to that category.

00:11:45.700 --> 00:11:49.739
So one of the things we'll do differently next time is to actually ask people to categorize

00:11:49.739 --> 00:11:54.460
themselves into experience levels to see if we might actually consider that to make sure

00:11:54.460 --> 00:11:58.700
that we're actually giving some awards to people who might be recently starting to work

00:11:58.700 --> 00:12:01.340
with Shiny as well.

00:12:01.340 --> 00:12:05.059
As I said, we looked through some of the code, and I think one of the really difficult things

00:12:05.059 --> 00:12:09.599
is to do code review across developers who don't work in the same framework.

00:12:09.599 --> 00:12:13.780
They might have choices they're making in terms of how they code up their app.

00:12:13.780 --> 00:12:15.140
That works for them.

00:12:15.140 --> 00:12:19.260
Maybe that is not how I do it or Joe does it or somebody else on the team does it.

00:12:19.260 --> 00:12:22.059
But there is no requirement of following a certain guideline.

00:12:22.059 --> 00:12:24.059
So that actually makes it really difficult.

00:12:24.059 --> 00:12:26.940
But I'll give you one example of one of our runner-ups.

00:12:26.940 --> 00:12:28.659
So this is a CRAN Explorer.

00:12:28.659 --> 00:12:30.659
It is not the only CRAN Explorer out there.

00:12:30.659 --> 00:12:34.659
But it is a really visually kind of striking CRAN Explorer.

00:12:34.659 --> 00:12:39.099
And one of the things we liked about this app was that it made really good use of HTML

00:12:39.099 --> 00:12:40.099
templates.

00:12:40.099 --> 00:12:44.539
And the code was written so nicely that you could really kind of factor out what parts

00:12:44.539 --> 00:12:50.099
of the code was building out the UI using the R and Shiny code and what parts of it

00:12:50.099 --> 00:12:51.460
was coming from HTML.

00:12:51.460 --> 00:12:56.460
So in this case, it was a little bit more straightforward to say, yes, this is well-written

00:12:56.460 --> 00:12:57.460
code.

00:12:57.460 --> 00:13:00.619
But I think that's a challenge that's just going to stick with the Shiny contest or any

00:13:00.619 --> 00:13:02.700
similar contest forever.

00:13:02.700 --> 00:13:05.419
Well, this one you can imagine.

00:13:05.419 --> 00:13:09.580
We should start reviewing them earlier because my guess is that curve is going to go up again

00:13:09.580 --> 00:13:11.299
closer to the deadline.

00:13:11.299 --> 00:13:14.479
So the review took a little bit longer than what we had promised.

00:13:14.479 --> 00:13:16.020
But now we have some more experience.

00:13:16.020 --> 00:13:19.619
So hopefully we'll be able to turn around the results a little bit faster.

00:13:19.659 --> 00:13:24.260
And I think it will be useful now that we've seen creativity from other contestants as

00:13:24.260 --> 00:13:29.299
to how they submitted their apps by providing more guidance for what makes a good submission.

00:13:29.299 --> 00:13:35.500
So one of the things is when you're posting on RStudio Community, so this is one of the

00:13:35.500 --> 00:13:41.219
runner-ups of the contest as well, give some more information than what's needed.

00:13:41.219 --> 00:13:43.340
This one was particularly long.

00:13:43.340 --> 00:13:47.780
But what you're seeing is there are some screenshots, there are some GIFs, and there's also narrative

00:13:47.780 --> 00:13:49.099
to go along with it.

00:13:49.099 --> 00:13:51.299
And I think this is really helpful.

00:13:51.299 --> 00:13:54.820
And also, you know, maybe you don't have the most performant app.

00:13:54.820 --> 00:13:59.580
But if you give me something to read through while that's loading, that's not a bad thing.

00:13:59.580 --> 00:14:03.940
The other thing is this idea of actually providing a walkthrough.

00:14:03.940 --> 00:14:08.580
So a few of the apps that were submitted had this where you come in and you don't have

00:14:08.580 --> 00:14:13.419
to just stare to see what you need to do or you don't have to just read static text.

00:14:13.419 --> 00:14:19.500
You can actually walk through the app, and that's how the developers decided to highlight

00:14:19.500 --> 00:14:21.580
the important features of the apps.

00:14:21.580 --> 00:14:27.020
Remember all of the contest submissions from last year are openly available still as posts

00:14:27.020 --> 00:14:29.820
on RStudio Community, whether they were winners or not.

00:14:29.820 --> 00:14:33.580
So if you would like to do something like that and are looking for the code, you should

00:14:33.580 --> 00:14:37.659
be able to go and track it down.

00:14:37.659 --> 00:14:39.020
So what's next?

00:14:39.020 --> 00:14:40.820
Well, two things.

00:14:40.820 --> 00:14:46.700
One is we have actually reinvented the Shiny User Showcase, and it's actually it sits along

00:14:46.700 --> 00:14:49.020
with the Shiny Gallery on the Dev Center.

00:14:49.020 --> 00:14:50.940
So this is the URL for it.

00:14:50.940 --> 00:14:55.820
And we have moved over the winning apps as well as many of the honorable mentions and

00:14:55.820 --> 00:15:01.260
runner-ups if the app developers agree to have their apps featured here.

00:15:01.260 --> 00:15:04.260
And we will be adding more to this.

00:15:04.260 --> 00:15:10.219
I actually have plans to add a form here so you can submit your app for consideration

00:15:10.219 --> 00:15:11.940
to be kept there.

00:15:11.940 --> 00:15:16.059
But I decided I'm going to hold off on it for a while, because for the next two months,

00:15:16.059 --> 00:15:18.380
you have a different way of submitting it.

00:15:18.380 --> 00:15:20.039
We have another contest.

00:15:20.039 --> 00:15:26.859
So I actually just posted this on RStudio Community, Shiny Contest 2020 is live.

00:15:26.859 --> 00:15:31.719
And what we're going to do this time is if you go to this community post, it will actually

00:15:31.719 --> 00:15:35.580
take you to a form that looks somewhat like a Google form, and it will feel restrictive

00:15:35.580 --> 00:15:41.299
initially, where we are asking you to put in certain pieces of information we want to

00:15:41.299 --> 00:15:45.099
make sure everybody has so that we can export this data easily.

00:15:45.099 --> 00:15:49.099
So in addition to your name or whatever, a description, and also giving you some guidance

00:15:49.099 --> 00:15:53.979
about how long these things should be, links to certain things we're requiring, what happens

00:15:53.979 --> 00:15:59.299
is once you submit that form, it actually turns into a community post, and you can do

00:15:59.299 --> 00:16:00.539
further editing there.

00:16:00.539 --> 00:16:04.260
So the idea is we're going to collect some information initially, but if you want to

00:16:04.260 --> 00:16:10.340
customize how you're presenting your app, you still have the opportunity to do so.

00:16:10.340 --> 00:16:15.260
So I usually give links to my slides at the end of my talk, but at this point, as I said,

00:16:15.260 --> 00:16:20.500
a lot of the work I presented is not really mine, but of the people who contributed to

00:16:20.500 --> 00:16:21.500
the contest.

00:16:21.500 --> 00:16:26.619
So up top is the link to the Shiny Gallery, and if you see any issues with any of the

00:16:26.619 --> 00:16:30.539
apps that are there, anything that's not working, I'm the person to contact, and I'd be happy

00:16:30.539 --> 00:16:32.260
to take care of that.

00:16:32.260 --> 00:16:36.739
And also the bottom link is the link to the Shiny Contest 2020.

00:16:36.739 --> 00:16:41.380
We are going to follow up with a blog post in the next week or so, but, hey, you guys

00:16:41.380 --> 00:16:46.059
are here, so you get a preview of it before the blog post goes live.

00:16:46.059 --> 00:16:47.059
Thank you very much.

00:16:47.059 --> 00:17:08.020
How do you build a walkthrough?

00:17:08.020 --> 00:17:13.979
So I don't know that I can actually walk you through how to build a walkthrough on the

00:17:13.979 --> 00:17:19.859
spot here, but what I can do is what we'll do in terms of the blog post that will follow

00:17:19.859 --> 00:17:25.420
up for what makes a good submission, I'd be happy to provide the links to some of the

00:17:25.420 --> 00:17:27.339
apps that actually did that.

00:17:27.339 --> 00:17:32.540
It requires a bit more than just using Shiny, but the code seems pretty reproducible to

00:17:32.540 --> 00:17:40.219
me, so I feel like it will be possible for somebody to learn from the code.

00:17:40.219 --> 00:17:45.459
Will there be a student category, like undergraduate students, possibly with the prize of free

00:17:45.459 --> 00:17:47.819
attendance at the conference next year?

00:17:47.819 --> 00:17:52.300
That question is above my pay grade.

00:17:52.300 --> 00:17:58.180
So I think the idea is that by asking for experience level, we are asking for so the

00:17:58.180 --> 00:18:03.859
cutoff is actually have you been building Shiny apps for less than a year or more?

00:18:03.859 --> 00:18:08.739
And we want to try to make sure that we're able to recognize some of the apps from people

00:18:08.739 --> 00:18:10.579
who have recently started as well.

00:18:10.579 --> 00:18:15.060
I would imagine that it's possible for an undergraduate student to fall into that.

00:18:15.060 --> 00:18:20.020
I don't know if one of the awards will be attendance, but I can tell you one of the

00:18:20.020 --> 00:18:24.819
really good awards is if you're one of the grand prize winners, you get a little bit

00:18:24.819 --> 00:18:29.180
of time with somebody from the Shiny team, like a 30-minute call where they can actually

00:18:29.180 --> 00:18:35.060
help you debug your app, and I feel like you probably can't put a price on that.

00:18:35.060 --> 00:18:41.140
In the gallery, will you list what packages each app depends on so we can find apps that

00:18:41.140 --> 00:18:44.500
use packages that we're interested in learning more about?

00:18:44.500 --> 00:18:45.500
That's a really good idea.

00:18:45.500 --> 00:18:50.560
So that is not something I pulled out, but that would be quite straightforward to do.

00:18:50.560 --> 00:18:53.660
So I will take that as a feature request.

00:18:53.660 --> 00:18:58.339
Currently the code is linked, so one could do that, but I will take a note of that, and

00:18:58.339 --> 00:19:01.660
I think that would be a good idea to include.

00:19:01.660 --> 00:19:08.579
If you ask people to rank their skills, won't they sandbag to increase their chances of

00:19:08.579 --> 00:19:09.579
winning?

00:19:09.579 --> 00:19:10.579
Probably not.

00:19:10.579 --> 00:19:11.579
Hopefully not.

00:19:11.579 --> 00:19:19.500
I'm going to say hopefully not, but I feel like the spirit of it is not necessarily to

00:19:19.500 --> 00:19:24.979
give anyone unfair advantage, but to make sure that people who may have just started

00:19:24.979 --> 00:19:29.579
working with Shiny actually feel welcome in the community.

00:19:29.579 --> 00:19:32.180
I am going to act optimistic for a second.

00:19:32.180 --> 00:19:37.500
I'm not known to be an optimist, but I think in this community people are going to want

00:19:37.500 --> 00:19:39.380
to encourage people to do that.

00:19:39.380 --> 00:19:44.819
I will also say that that's not going to be like a straight cut threshold for ranking

00:19:44.819 --> 00:19:45.819
apps.

00:19:45.819 --> 00:19:49.660
It's just I want to make sure that we're able to recognize some of the people who feel like

00:19:49.660 --> 00:19:53.500
they are new to this and take a look to see if there's something that we might be able

00:19:53.500 --> 00:19:55.140
to acknowledge there.

00:19:56.140 --> 00:20:04.140
Finally, there's a question about the rubric, and will it be shared in an article?

00:20:04.140 --> 00:20:05.140
Yeah.

00:20:05.140 --> 00:20:11.819
So now that we have developed a rubric, the blog post that I'll write, I'll actually add

00:20:11.819 --> 00:20:18.579
to it in terms of what the selection criteria look like, and one thing I'll highlight from

00:20:18.579 --> 00:20:25.219
a rubric is that we gave equal points to technical merit and visual appeal, just basically

00:20:25.219 --> 00:20:29.260
acknowledging that some people like working on one aspect and some people like working

00:20:29.260 --> 00:20:33.020
on the other, and ultimately we'd want to recognize both of them.

00:20:33.020 --> 00:20:34.020
All right.

00:20:34.020 --> 00:20:35.020
Thank you.

00:20:35.020 --> 00:20:36.020
Thank you, Mine.

00:20:36.020 --> 00:20:37.020
Thank you, Mine.

00:20:37.020 --> 00:20:38.020
All right.

00:20:38.020 --> 00:20:39.020
It looks like that's it for our questions.

00:20:39.020 --> 00:20:40.020
All right.

